compartment_id, display_name, id,
lifecycle_state
conflicts: none
open gaps: none
Queue create, update, and delete are
work-request-backed. The runtime projects the
polled work request into status.async.current as
the canonical async tracker, while
createWorkRequestId, updateWorkRequestId, and
deleteWorkRequestId remain compatibility mirrors
so reconcile resumes asynchronous OCI operations
across requeues instead of relying on name-only
lookup.
Queue SDK OperationStatus values normalize into
shared async classes and Queue ActionType values
normalize into create, update, and delete
phases, but raw work-request status, operation
type, message, percent complete, and work
request ID stay visible in status for debugging.
Create binds identity from Queue work-request
resources, then reads the Queue by recovered
OCID before projecting status. Delete is not
best-effort; it only completes after GetQueue
confirms the tracked Queue is gone or exposes
lifecycle state DELETED.
Mutable drift is limited to UpdateQueueDetails
fields such as capabilities, displayName,
timeout, visibility, tags,
channelConsumptionLimit,
deadLetterQueueDeliveryCount, and
customEncryptionKeyId. Queue steady-state parity
treats capabilities as the enabled type set
because GetQueue does not echo consumer-group
add-on settings after enablement, even though
the runtime still forwards repo-authored
capability payloads on create and update when
that set changes.
A package-local companion writes or updates the
same-name endpoint Secret only after ACTIVE when
messagesEndpoint is present, adopts only
unlabeled matching Secrets, uses guarded
updates/deletes for owned Secrets, and skips
missing or unowned Secrets during delete
cleanup.
end note
